I'm selling my barely-used Sig Sauer Mosquito 22LR. I'd be surprised if this has more than 250 rounds through it. Anytime it has been taken to the range it has been carefully cleaned afterwards (and I doubt it's been to the range more than 5 times).

The Mosquito is 90% of the size of the P226 and is a great gun. Easy (and inexpensive) to shoot.

I have a friend who had never really fired a handgun before who was going through her CCW training course. With barely any practice (less than 10 rounds) she qualified with this firearm.

Why did I buy it? It's a Sig Sauer. Plus, a 22LR. And, it has a thumb safety (important feature for me: I know, lots of people don't use them and I understand). However, I haven't purchased any other Sig Sauer's and am now standardizing on Ruger's (and, of all things, the Ruger thumb safeties flip the opposite direction).

You can see the condition of the firearm in the photos. Included with the gun:
- 1x 10-round Sig OEM factory magazine
- The original case
- Registration card, user manual
- Ruger gun lock
- Spare recoil spring (the reason many semi-automatic 22's have a reputation for not reliably feeding ammunition is the varying quality of 22LR ammunition - to give you an idea of Sig Sauer quality: they knew that is what causes issues with semi-automatic 22's and included two springs with the Mosquito --- a stiffer one that works best with higher-powered/premium 22 ammo, and a looser spring that works better with bulk/regular 22 ammo). Speaking of how the firearm handles 22 ammo: it's done quite well, and I just use bulk 22 (not the higher-powered 22). I don't know if I have the stiffer or looser recoil spring currently in the firearm.

The major difference between the M95 and the M90 is that the pistol grip and trigger have been moved forward 1 inch (25 mm) for better magazine clearance. Also, the bolt handle has been redesigned and bent down and to the rear, the barrel chamber has been plated in chrome, and there are also some minor changes to the trigger and firing pin.

The Model 95 may weigh in at a smaller class, but packed into its convenient bullpup design are the intense power of a magazine-fed weapon, the pinpoint accuracy of a bolt action rifle and the effortless functionality of a perfectly designed machine.

This compact rifle offers the velocity and accuracy of a 29-inch barrel in a shortened overall length of just 45 inches. Adopted for military use, the Model 95 is made for those who refuse to sacrifice accuracy for power.

Its buttplate, magazine well and trigger housing are unitized, helping to stiffen the steel lower receiver. the steel upper receiver is reinforced with an M1913 optics rail and supports the chrome-chambered, fluted barrel. the two can be assembled in less than 60 seconds without the use of tools.

The bolt carrier itself is a study in innovation. Designed for speed, reliability and safety, it slides effortlessly on machined-smooth parallel rails, transporting a large bolt that locks into the barrel extension on three lugs. The firing pin is driven by dual firing pin springs designed for consistency and lightning-quick lock time.

The only thing more impressive than the Model 95 rifle’s performance is the comfort with which it can be used. the ergonomically designed rifle rests on a lightweight front bipod and an optional adjustable rear monopod. this careful attention to usability allows the shooter to quickly and accurately fire five rounds, reload with a fresh magazine and get back on target in seconds.

NEW FA BOLT CARRIER GROUP (BCG) for SEMI-AUTOMATIC AR STYLE RIFLES.  This BCG is used for the AR Rifles chambered in 5.56x45, 223, and 300 AAC Blackout.  Item was tested at factory prior to shipping to ensure functionality.

DETAILS: same bcg used by multiple US manufacturers,  standard bolt carrier group, black phosphate finish, bolt percision machined from 9310 steel, carrier percision machined from 8620 alloy steel billet, chrome lined carrier, gas key screws are hardened and properly staked, bolts manufactured to US MilSpec prints, firing pin is hardened solid stainless, bolt is EDI and MPI tested and shot peened.

Price include shipping via USPS Priority with tracking number.
